bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: This collection contains the personal items of Cornwall minister and historian, Edward Comfort Starr (1844-1941).Starr was born in Guilford, Connecticut on January 12, 1844 to John and Lydia Starr. In 1866, Starr graduated from Yale College, and three years later graduated from Yale Seminary. As a Congregationalist minister, Starr was formally ordained in Waseca, Minnesota in 1871, and served the Congregationalist church there for five years before removing to the Wethersfield Avenue Church in Hartford. While working in Hartford, Starr married Emily Amelia Shew in 1878, and the couple ultimately had three children, Charles, Edward, and Mabel. In 1881, due to health reasons, Starr was transferred to the community of Northfield, Connecticut, where he preached for six years before being reassigned to Cornwall in 1888.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: As a pastor at Cornwall’s First Church, Starr took a special interest in the community’s history.A prolific researcher and writer, Starr collected hundreds of items related to Cornwall’s past, ultimately culminating in the 1926 publication of his book, A History of Cornwall, Connecticut: A Typical New England Town. Starr’s personal items later formed the basis for the Cornwall Historical Society’s collections. Starr served the First Church until 1915, and remained in the community following his resignation. Following his death on January 16, 1941, his collections were given to the Cornwall Library, and were transferred to the Cornwall Historical Society upon its incorporation in 1964.

arrangement.p: The files are grouped into 3 series:
